its not intrinsic value that "bounces around." It is share prices that bounce around based on sentiment and a number of other issues - that provides the opportunity to buy at disct to intrinsic or short at premium to intrinsic.

I dont think you understand or maybe dont appreciate value of fundamental input that creates the calculus of intrinsic value. Read Graham and Dodd. It seems to have worked out well for practioners like Cooperman, Loeb, Buffett, Gabelli et al. Moreover, in terms of your comment...

My intrinsic value or "fair market value" for the S&P (about 2450) has not changed for over a year. As prices rose well above I shorted in exposure. As prices fall to a discount I trade on the long side. This calculus has allowed me to trade opportunistically and unemotionally.
This calculus has helped me deliver superior returns this year. As I say to you, "horses for courses." Or as Grandma Koufax used to say, "Do it the way you do it and do it well."

Mr. Toad's Wild Ride on @realmoney The spastic action, like Mr. Toad's Wild Ride at Disneyland underscores the following: * We are in a new regime of unprecedented volatility (something I have been predicting since early January 2018)

* Volatility is the outgrowth of lower liquidity - get used to it * Machines and algos are moving stocks to the degree not seen in years - they are agnostic to fundamentals and create abrupt and artificial market moves * Avoid the self confident in view and hide your children

and portfolios away from them as the only certainty in these markets are the lack of uncertainty. * Reduce exposure size and keep your portfolio's "VAR" (value at risk) lower than normal if you cherish your capital and P&L * It is important not to lose your head when many

are losing theirs * Stay focused, always assess reward v. risk, stick with your risk profile/appetite, and consider your trading and investing time frames. * Trade unemotionally and opportunistically (I am!)
